Node.js File System (fs) – Complete Guide

The File System (fs) module allows Node.js to read, write, update, delete, and stream files and directories on the server.

Node.js provides 3 ways to work with files:

Synchronous (Blocking)

Asynchronous – Callback-based

Asynchronous – Promise-based

Streams (for large files)

1️⃣ Importing the File System Module
const fs = require("fs");              // Callback & Sync API
const fsPromises = require("fs/promises"); // Promise-based API

2️⃣ Synchronous File Operations (Blocking)
🔹 What it means

Blocks the event loop

No other request is processed until the operation finishes

NOT recommended for production servers

🔹 When to use

CLI tools

Startup configuration

Small scripts

Example: Read File (Sync)
const data = fs.readFileSync("data.txt", "utf8");
console.log(data);

Example: Write File (Sync)
fs.writeFileSync("log.txt", "Server started");


❌ Bad for APIs – slows down all users.

3️⃣ Asynchronous File Operations (Callback-based)
🔹 Why this is important

Non-blocking

Other requests continue processing

Core strength of Node.js

Example: Read File (Async)
fs.readFile("data.txt", "utf8", (err, data) => {
  if (err) {
    console.error(err);
    return;
  }
  console.log(data);
});

Example: Write File (Async)
fs.writeFile("output.txt", "Hello Node.js", err => {
  if (err) throw err;
  console.log("File written");
});

4️⃣ Promise-based File System (fs/promises) ✅ Best Practice
🔹 Why preferred

Cleaner syntax

Works perfectly with async/await

Better error handling

Example: Read File
const fs = require("fs/promises");

async function readFile() {
  try {
    const data = await fs.readFile("data.txt", "utf8");
    console.log(data);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err);
  }
}

Example: Write File
await fs.writeFile("file.txt", "Saved using promises");

5️⃣ Creating & Deleting Files
Create File
await fs.writeFile("new.txt", "New file created");

Delete File
await fs.unlink("new.txt");

❗ Error Scenario

If file doesn’t exist:

ENOENT: no such file or directory


Always wrap in try/catch.

6️⃣ Append Data to a File (Logging Scenario)
Real-world use

Logs

Audit trails

Chat history

await fs.appendFile("logs.txt", "User logged in\n");

7️⃣ Working with Directories
Create Directory
await fs.mkdir("uploads");

Create Nested Directories
await fs.mkdir("a/b/c", { recursive: true });

Read Directory Contents
const files = await fs.readdir("./uploads");
console.log(files);

Delete Directory
await fs.rmdir("uploads", { recursive: true });

8️⃣ File Information (Stats)
Check if File or Directory
const stats = await fs.stat("data.txt");

console.log(stats.isFile());      // true
console.log(stats.isDirectory()); // false

File Size
console.log(stats.size); // bytes

9️⃣ Check if File Exists (IMPORTANT)

❌ Deprecated

fs.existsSync("file.txt");


✅ Recommended

try {
  await fs.access("file.txt");
  console.log("File exists");
} catch {
  console.log("File does not exist");
}

🔟 Rename / Move Files
await fs.rename("old.txt", "new.txt");


Move file:

await fs.rename("temp/file.txt", "uploads/file.txt");

1️⃣1️⃣ Streams (VERY IMPORTANT)
🔹 Why streams?

Handles large files

Uses less memory

Processes data in chunks

Example: Read Stream
const stream = fs.createReadStream("large.mp4");

stream.on("data", chunk => {
  console.log(chunk.length);
});

Example: Copy Large File
const read = fs.createReadStream("video.mp4");
const write = fs.createWriteStream("copy.mp4");

read.pipe(write);

1️⃣2️⃣ File Upload Scenario (Express)
app.post("/upload", (req, res) => {
  const writeStream = fs.createWriteStream("file.txt");

  req.pipe(writeStream);

  req.on("end", () => {
    res.send("Upload complete");
  });
});

1️⃣3️⃣ Error Handling (CRITICAL)
Common Errors
Error Code	Meaning
ENOENT	File not found
EACCES	Permission denied
EISDIR	Path is directory
Proper Handling
try {
  await fs.readFile("secret.txt");
} catch (err) {
  if (err.code === "ENOENT") {
    console.log("File not found");
  }
}

1️⃣4️⃣ Security Best Practices ⚠️

❌ Never allow direct file paths from users:

fs.readFile(req.query.file); // DANGEROUS


✅ Always validate:

path.join(__dirname, "files", filename);

1️⃣5️⃣ Performance Best Practices

✅ Use async or promises
✅ Use streams for large files
❌ Avoid sync methods in servers
❌ Avoid loading large files into memory

🔚 Summary

✔ Sync – scripts, CLI
✔ Async – APIs
✔ Promises – best choice
✔ Streams – large files
✔ Always handle errors
✔ Validate paths